title: Video: Michael Conforto provides Mets with go-ahead strikeout in Game 3
text:
Sometimes great effort trumps superior talent in the MLB playoffs.
Mets left fielder Michael Conforto didn’t earn a hit to score teammate Yoenis Cespedes, but his hustle was enough to bring in a run.
In the sixth inning, Conforto swung on a wild pitch but didn’t make contact. The ball got away from the Cubs’ catcher and Cespedes scored easily.
. @ynscspds and @mconforto8 proved three strikes doesn't necessarily mean you're out: https://t.co/Jj12nYEGnV pic.twitter.com/9jj0tMhPzW
— Cut4 (@Cut4) October 21, 2015
It wasn’t the best play, but it was a mighty heady one. Who knows if Conforto meant to strikeout; its not that important. The key was that he scored a run in a time when his team needed it most, and in playoff baseball, that’s all you need.
Michael Conforto: 2nd go-ahead strikeout in postseason history
David Murphy strikeout in 2011 ALDS Game 2, Adrian Beltre scored
— ESPN Stats & Info (@ESPNStatsInfo) October 21, 2015
